# Storytelling Reference

Based on [The Complete Story Telling Course for Speaking & Presenting](https://www.udemy.com/course/the-complete-storytelling-course-for-speaking-presenting/)
by [TJ Walker](https://www.udemy.com/user/tjwalker2).

## Become a Master Storyteller

### Quick Story

- Think of anyone who has annoyed you recently, or who is annoyed.
- Could be a customer, client, or colleague. Could be a call, email, or text.
- What was the problem? What was it about?
- How did you help this person?
- How were they feeling? How were you feeling?
- Retell real experiences with real colleagues, clients, and customers.

### What to Cut When Time is Short

- Everyone remembers stories. No one complains about telling too many stories.
- Don't cut the stories.
- No one remembers facts, data, or figures.

### How to Start a Presentation

- Don't introduce yourself.
- Don't explain how good you are, what credentials you have, what books you have written, or how long you have been doing this.
- Don't thank the audience or say how happy you are to be here today. That is boring.
- Don't talk about yourself. Don't defend your right to speak.
- Launch right into a story. It lightens the mood, makes the presentation more interesting, and is the best way to start.

### No Natural Born Storytellers

- Storytelling is a learned behaviour. Get up and talk. Stand up and speak.
- Tell a story to make a point.
- If you say something quickly, briefly, or at an abstract level, nobody remembers it.
- Stories are memorable. People remember stories, not facts.
- Stories make the point more visual and slow it down, making impact more likely.

## How to Write a Great Presentation

1. Brainstorm for messages and actions. What do you want the audience to remember? What do you want them to do?
2. Identify the one Action you want your audience to take.
3. Identify the top 5 Messages to back up the Action. If you have more, throw them away.
4. Identify an Example, Case Study, or Story for each of the 5 Messages.
5. Write it all down in big bold font. Print it out. Leave copies around the room: one on the lectern, one near your water on the table, one at the back of the room so you can walk around.
6. Identify an image for each of the 5 Messages. Use Google Image Search. If you can't find an image, leave the slide blank.
7. Don't start with a title page. Leave the first slide blank.
8. Everything you used to put into slides, write up as a document or Confluence page and share it before the presentation.
9. If you need a graph or table in a slide, make it super simple. Put the complex data into the document.

